items.name: Joseph Wright Of Derby Style
items.description:
Joseph Wright of Derby, born in 1734, was an English painter known for his skillful use of light and shadow in his works. He was one of the prominent figures of the English Enlightenment period and is often referred to as "Wright of Derby" due to his association with the city of Derby in England.

Wright's paintings encompassed a variety of genres, including portraiture, landscapes, and historical scenes. However, he is most renowned for his mastery of capturing the effects of light in his works, particularly in his candlelit scenes and industrial landscapes.

One of his notable series is the "Candlelight" series, where he depicted individuals or groups illuminated by a single light source, creating dramatic contrasts between light and dark. These works demonstrated his technical skill in rendering the subtleties of light and shadow, and they often evoked a sense of mystery and introspection.

Wright also explored the emerging industrial revolution in his paintings, depicting scenes of factories, ironworks, and scientific experiments. His works captured the awe and curiosity associated with the advancements of the time.

Throughout his career, Wright received patronage from influential figures, including prominent scientists and industrialists. His paintings were highly regarded for their technical precision and the emotive atmosphere they conveyed.

Joseph Wright of Derby's contributions to art during the Enlightenment era marked a significant shift in artistic subject matter and techniques. His skillful handling of light and his ability to capture the human spirit in various contexts solidified his reputation as one of the great painters of his time. Today, his works can be found in museums and galleries, where they continue to inspire and intrigue viewers with their mastery of light and profound subject matter.

items.name: Josh Agle Style
items.description:
Josh Agle, commonly known by his pseudonym Shag, is an American artist known for his distinctive retro-style illustrations and paintings. Born in 1962, Agle's artwork often captures the spirit of mid-century modern design and popular culture.

Shag's artistic style is characterized by bold, flat colors, clean lines, and a playful sense of humor. His works often depict stylized figures, sleek architecture, and scenes of leisure, evoking a nostalgic aesthetic reminiscent of the 1950s and 1960s.

Inspired by mid-century advertising, architecture, fashion, and music, Shag's art captures the vibrant and carefree lifestyle associated with that era. His compositions are filled with intriguing narratives and details, inviting viewers to step into a world of retro-cool.

In addition to his paintings, Shag's artwork has been featured in various forms, including prints, merchandise, and album covers. His collaborations with fashion brands, music groups, and cultural events have further solidified his influence in the world of contemporary pop art.

Shag's popularity has grown over the years, and his artwork has gained a dedicated following. His unique blend of vintage aesthetics, modern sensibilities, and a touch of whimsy have made him a recognizable and influential figure in the realm of pop art.

Josh Agle, or Shag, continues to create vibrant and nostalgic artwork that captures the essence of mid-century modern aesthetics. His signature style has found a special place in contemporary art, offering viewers a glimpse into a stylish and imaginative world filled with retro charm.

items.name: Josh Kirby Style
items.description:
Josh Kirby a British artist and illustrator known for his work in the science fiction and fantasy genres. He was particularly renowned for his cover art for the Discworld series of books by Terry Pratchett.

Kirby's illustrations were characterized by their dynamic and vivid style. His artwork often featured intricate details, vibrant colors, and a sense of whimsy. He had a knack for capturing the essence of fantastical worlds and characters, bringing them to life on the covers of books.

One of his most significant contributions was his collaboration with Terry Pratchett on the Discworld series, where his cover art became synonymous with the beloved fantasy series. Kirby's illustrations skillfully captured the humor, wit, and eccentricity of Pratchett's writing, becoming an integral part of the Discworld universe.

Beyond the Discworld series, Kirby's artwork graced the covers of numerous other science fiction and fantasy novels, showcasing his versatility as an artist. His illustrations often conveyed a sense of adventure and wonder, transporting readers into imaginative realms.

Kirby's talent and impact on the science fiction and fantasy community were widely recognized. His artwork continues to be celebrated for its dynamic energy, meticulous details, and ability to capture the essence of fantastical worlds.

Josh Kirby's contributions as an illustrator enriched the reading experience for countless fans of science fiction and fantasy literature. His distinctive style and imaginative artwork left an indelible mark on the genre, and his legacy lives on through his iconic cover illustrations.

items.name: XenoREALITY
items.description:
That's Not Real, That's Xeno Real!

This model represents my first foray into more realistic models. It is designed for both portraits and scenery. At this stage, it is not particularly great at scenes with people in extreme positions - but I think I'm on the right track. It's a lot better than my last few methods of achieving this goal.

This model is not inherently capable of porn (though all of your LoRa's should work - please do share your successes and failures so I can get an idea of what needs the most work.)

This model does tend to go nude fairly easily, though.

If you test and play with this model, please show me some of your failures and successes (and please don't just tank the review ratings without at least some clues and information I can use to try to fix the problem). There WILL be issues compared to many of the more mature and stable models, but with your help I can make this great and provide some unique things not seen in other photo real models.

Like it? Buy me a beer. * Shoutout and Thank you to Arpigeon for the beer! I will be enjoying it and sending you a toast during my Friday Happy Hour this week!


Join the XenoEngine Discord to discuss tips and tricks, complimentary Lora's and Embeds, and to post (and see) images not allowed here on Civitai.

V2.0 - True Grit

V2 should push even harder toward "realistic photography" while still taking on characteristics of various art styles and so on. While it may be difficult in some cases to get an art style looking like drawn art - it WILL tend to take on other elements of that style (shaping, outfit selection, etc) while maintaining a "real" look and feel to things. Your default people and their looks will be more raw and gritty, while still hopefully being attractive (and you can always "hollywoodize" everyone with various beauty and attractiveness statements too).

RC 1

From the very beginning of this learning process (with my XenoEngine models) I've been working on trying to create a versatile model that will work well on "Potato" computers (i.e. LowVRAM and NoGPU environments) in order to create game character assets for games. This means we want to be able to generate consistent characters in different outfits and styles without big long prompts and without needing to make 20 attempts just to get something decent or that doesn't need 3 hours of post work just to get ready to start doing background removal and optimizing for game use. This would be for 2D game engines like RPG Maker (character busts), Twine, RenPy (and other visual novel systems) and so on.

This Release Candidate represents what I think just might be very close to having accomplished that. These last optimizations work really well (most of the preview images I'm going to post to start were done on a No GPU Huggingface Space). Memory optimizations seem really good - and I'll be posting some tips and recommendations over the coming days as we run what I hope is the final round before an official release of the model.

Some key changes in this:

  • Memory Optimization: All along, I've been trying to test (and lately, I've even been performing the merges themselves) on both T4 GPU environments AND No GPU and LowVRAM systems. XenoEngine ArtStyle never really worked that well for the Potato Computer systems, but I still love it for higher end installs. Each of the next two (XenoEngine 5th Dimension and 6th Sense) got a little better at it. This one... well, it looks pretty good (until you try to jam too much action and specific elements to include in an image). And, of course, it looks even better for these situations on a proper rig.

  • More Outfit Diversity: While I feel that the outfits that come out when you just generally describe them (e.g. "Business Suit" or "Bimbocore Outfit") are less "sexy" by default - the potential variation while still saying on theme is greater. (And you can still get to those sexier outfits by being a bit more comprehensive in your description of what you want them wearing.)

GPU vs. NoGPU Examples:

GPU Examples

NoGPU Examples: Random Female Celebrities / Random Male Celebrities (Soon) / Various Random Art & Composition Styles

BETA 2

This is an update that is mostly sanity fixes - better default camera positioning, better fallback lighting and composition when you don't declare anything, and a bunch of new outfits. As you can see from the comparison images, the changes are subtle for most complicated prompts with lots of direction - but simple prompts have a much greater change.

Concept Blending is working really well and over a much wider range of concepts now, too. Here are some examples with a brief description. it's REALLY cool and fun to play with if you haven't done it before.

Main Goals for Model

  • Improved Character Sculpting Controls: One of the things I love about the comic/cartoon based models is that they tend to have much more effective and comprehensive body controls - but the reality based ones are much more limited. It makes sense. For example - source images that show lots of different breast sizes - especially ones in that show comparison, differences, progressions, and high range sizes are digital art coming out of the fetish community. As such, as soon as you start applying those changes, your image starts to shift away from real toward the style of the source images. The bigger the shape change, the more the style is going to change.

    I've developed a recipe, though, which allows me to get in (some of) those controls with only moderate effect on things. At this point you can make some small to moderate changes without much change. Larger changes start to move it toward looking like a 3D render a bit more than a photo. The main issue now is a loss of skin detail - which may be able to be brought back with some clever prompting (let me know if you find something) but I'm also working on it from this end, too.

  • Smart & Consistent Default Fallback Tendencies: When we run a prompt that is missing something like a lighting, scene description, camera angle, and so on - SD will use it's (sic) Intelligence to make that choice for us. In my other models, they did a pretty good job of this - but all the tendencies and things I put in there were all based upon things that relate to the overall drawing/rendering style - not lighting and quality/reality tags and all that stuff.

    Right now, if you just put a subject name and a simple action or description, the output is just sort of flat and boring. An early experiment I did got some nice detail and effect going - but it wasn't consistent. It might choose a nice golden hour in one shot and then, same prompt, different seed, light it completely differently. That's not what I want - I want it at least somewhat consistent for story tellers and game makers.

    For now, make sure you're including some lighting, style/quality, and other appropriate tokens to get that "finished look" going. Those triggers won't change, but hopefully I can get it so it's making good choices so you don't NEED to put all the gazillion tokens in there just to get a halfway decent picture.

  • Lots More: There are a zillion things this model already does well - things that you don't necessarily see very often in realistic models. I want to get to uploading this thing so you can play with it though.

    Look for updates on this page (even when the model doesn't update) and I'll also be posting some articles with tips and tricks and all that fun stuff.

Again - this is BETA, but still already slightly above average for a checkpoint, IMO. Don't expect perfection, yet, and please share issues, and problems (and successes, too!) so that I can address them - either by helping you figure how to prompt your way out of it, or to make adjustments in the model itself (if possible).

v2.0 - True Grit Edition
I've always hesitated to update this model because anything which added functionality always took away from realism. As such, I've left this alone thinking that I'd only bother with an update if I could manage up the "reality factor" at least as much as the functional factor.

Well... that day has come.

V2 should push even harder toward "realistic photography" while still taking on characteristics of various art styles and so on. Your default people and their looks will be more raw and gritty, while still hopefully being attractive (and you can always "hollywoodize" everyone with various beauty and attractiveness statements too).

Play with it and let me know what you think!

modelVersions.name: v1.0
modelVersions.description:
This is the "Official Launch" version. Changes from the RC1 version are minor, but will change things up a bit.

  • Slightly increased the weight of the Anthromorph/Creature/Alien hybrid elements a bit to make it, hopefully, take a bit less weight to get things moving on entities which have higher epoch's. (Basically what that means is that it can take some extra work to make a "Wolf Girl" out of "Emma Watson" because it's always trying to make the wolf head look like Emma - so you need to crank up the weights compared to just making a generic "Wolf Girl" that can look however it wants. This tweak makes it take less "push" to get things happening.

  • Default lighting for "photo" and "realistic" type images should be slightly "brighter" but also potentially have a bit more "contrast" depending upon the environment. This is probably a bit more noticeable indoors than out.

  • Slightly less default detail in scenes. You can still amp up the details using my Xeno Magic Detailer (see recommendations list for the model), many other available LoRa's and Embeds, and just using the standard details prompts. (e.g. "add detail", "extremely detailed background" or whatever).

modelVersions.name: BETA 2
modelVersions.description: Lots of great stuff in this - better automatic camera positioning, LOTS more outfit variety when you refer to them by style or even not declaring clothes at all, and concept blending.

items.name: UFOMaker
items.description:
UFOMaker is a tool for generating all types of UFOs and spaceships. It was trained on an in-house developed dataset of 360 designs with interesting concept features (this is my most time-consuming model project yet). The dataset was partially created as Blender ControlNet inputs for AI generation or hand retouched from generated sketches:

The model either fixes the original input or makes it more interesting.

Use Hires. fix (4x_RealisticRescaler, 4x-Ultrasharp upscalers with denoising strength around 0.3-0.6) for best details in txt2img!

Experiment with weights around 0.1-1 (see above image, the lower values will modify the design, higher will create more asset type picture) , CLIP SKIP 1-2 . The model works with ufo and spaceship tokens (try to use a combination ufo|spaceship, ufo:spaceship:ufo, and so on). It will also style a combined vehicle.

LyCORIS/LoHA experiment trained 512x512, NR 64 + NA 32 dimensions. I am not aiming for technical realism with this series, the models are more focused on design ideas. If you want to learn more about AI-augmented design and algorithmic art, check my web pages.

For my notes on training, research, and use of stable diffusion models, check https://sandner.art/articles/ai/

If you can afford it, support my work by buying me a coffee to keep those costly render cores go and to keep creative flow of this content: https://ko-fi.com/airesearch

If you can not, review an rate the model to help others to find it.

Plans for further development

  • Train for higher res with updated dataset

  • Actions and technical details training (for next versions)

  • Optimize the training

  • Optimize the dataset

  • Create more focused Light version

Have fun rendering!

items.name: Graphic XL (for SD1.5)
items.description:
Introducing Graphic XL Model: An AI Model for Generating Graphic Art

Graphic XL Model is a powerful AI model specifically designed to generate visually striking and captivating graphic art. Trained on StableDiffusionXL results focused on graphic art, this model has undergone 20 epochs and 2840 steps to master the intricate patterns, vibrant colors, and unique visual elements characteristic of graphic design.

The training process of Graphic XL Model involved utilizing a curated dataset derived from StableDiffusionXL's results, emphasizing graphic art styles and techniques. The dataset encompasses a diverse range of graphic design elements, including geometric shapes, textures, color palettes, and composition principles. Through this training, Graphic XL Model has acquired a deep understanding of the visual aesthetics and principles that drive graphic art.

items.name: Z_phyr Reborn
items.description:
Warning: contains both safe and unsafe content.

A lot of time has passed since I posted my first checkpoint. Now I can’t even imagine how this stillborn thing could work at all. It’s pointless to keep supporting it, but it has some advantages too — a relatively high level of realism. So I decided to start a parallel branch of training. And the Mix is merged only on those layers that are responsible for the sense of realism. I fixed the CLIP issue, the memory leak problem, and cut out those checkpoints that have a non-free license from the Mix.

All examples are generated without face restoration and hires fix.

Contains noise offset.

警告：包含安全和不安全的内容。

自从我发布了我的第一个检查点以来，已经过了很长时间。现在我甚至无法想象这个夭折的东西到底是怎么运作的。继续支持它是没有意义的，但它也有一些优点——相对较高的真实感水平。所以我决定开始一个并行的训练分支。而 Mix 只是合并了那些负责真实感的层。CLIP 修复，内存泄漏修复，从 Mix 中剪切掉那些有非自由许可证的检查点。

所有的例子都是没有 face restoration 和 hires fix 的生成的。

包含 noise offset。

Предупреждение: включает как безопасное, так и небезопасное содержимое.

Много времени прошло с тех пор, как я выложил свой первый чекпоинт. Сейчас я даже не представляю, как это мертворождённое нечто вообще могло работать. Продолжать поддерживать его бессмысленно, тем не менее, плюсы у него тоже есть — относительно высокий уровень реалистичности. Поэтому мной было принято решение начать параллельную ветку обучения. А сам Микс замерджен только на тех слоях, которые отвечают за ощущение реалистичности. Фикс КЛИПа, исправление утечек памяти, из Микса вырезаны те чекпоинты, которые имеют несвободную лицензию.

Все примеры сгенерированы без face restoration и hires fix.

Содержит noise offset.

Geometric Woman Model is specifically designed to generate visually captivating compositions that combine geometric elements with female subjects. Trained for 20 epochs and 3200 steps, this model has honed its ability to seamlessly blend geometric shapes and patterns with the graceful form of the female figure.

During its training process, Geometric Woman Model was exposed to a curated dataset consisting of images that featured a combination of geometric compositions and female subjects. The dataset encompassed a wide range of artistic styles, including abstract and contemporary approaches to geometric design. By analyzing and learning from this dataset, the model gained a deep understanding of how to harmoniously integrate geometric shapes with the beauty and elegance of the female form.

items.name: Kaiju Toy Cards トイカード
items.description:
This model has been trained on collectible cards printed in Japan between 1989 and 1992, depicting kaiju such as Godzilla, Hedorah, Mothra, and King Ghidorah. Each card came with a coded message, and vital statistics about the beast it portrayed.

Stable Diffusion is notoriously bad at replicating numbers and letters, but the bright colours and retro charm of the original cards shine through, allowing you to generate your own army of monsters.

items.name: Nidalee - League of Legends | Character LoRA
items.description:
If you enjoyed this model, why don't you check out my other works? I put a lot of effort into correctly recreating artist styles and making the occasional character LoRA.😊

This model was trained using the collab/guide by holostrawberry [Guide] Make your own Loras, easy and free - colabs | Stable Diffusion Other | Civitai

Weights and Prompts

The basic prompt is

Nidalee

v2.0

I recommend a weight of 1.0.

Lower weights can still work but tend to lose some details of the base skin in particular. Check the XYZ plot and the notes for more details.

In did this version without specific clothing prompts. You can get pretty good versions of the same skins as v1.0 with

Basic:

loincloth

(isn't strictly necessary but sometimes she only wears panties without the prompt)

Maid:

maid, maid headdress, maid apron, thighhighs

And some that kind off work:

Witch:

witch, short hair, thighhighs, hat, dress, cleavage, bare shoulders, yellow eyes, boots, striped, puffy sleeves, witch hat, corset, striped thighhighs, halloween

Pharaoh:

 (egyptian, egyptian clothes, medium hair,bob cut, gorget, armlet, tiara, blunt bangs, gold, white skirt, dark skin:1.2)

this one is already pretty sketchy.

It is generally a lot more flexible so by playing around with hair color, hair styles, clothing patterns and general clothing prompts, getting something resembling most of her other skins should be possible.

v1.0

I generally used a weight of 1.0.

For clothing options use

basic_skin, maid_skin

This is an experimental LoRA. It looks like the maid clothes can easily bleed into the other clothing option. Furthermore I needed to go quite high in the generation for the clothing to be accurate but that means they are in turn much harder to replace or remove. Weirdly enough for RevAnimated it tends to generate the basic clothes even when prompted the other way

Some sideeffects of the low sample size are that sometimes random animals (as in deformed cats) show up or SD tries to generate some sort of (curved) spear.

Please leave a review if you enjoyed this model or have problems with it. This helps me with improving future models and finetuning them in general. Give it a try and throw some images down below! 👇
